In article <1994Jan31.221118.23325@ringer.cs.utsa.edu>
           dwomack@runner "David L Womack" writes:
>
> I've been wondering...about how many calculations\
> does it take to break a 1024 bit RSA key?  And,

The best general attack is factoring your public key.  This would take a very
long time with known factoring methods, longer than the life of the universe!

> how hard is it to break the password protection
> for the keyrings?  ...

Your private keyring is encrypted with IDEA, using the MD5 hash of your
password.  If your password is in a dictionary this is easy to break, if
you use an unpredictable pass phrase it is much harder (eg nonsense words
a line from a book - backwards, ...)

> ... I'm sure this has been answered
> before, but I was hoping for a fairly straightforward
> answer.  Many thanks for your help.

For more info look in alt.security.pgp newsgroup.

